    "question_id" : 53565210,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Delegate the responsibility of checking for <code>null</code> to the super class instead.</p>\n\n<pre><code>public class Car extends Vehicle {\n    public Car (Car a) {\n        super(a);\n    }\n}\n\npublic class Vehicle {\n    public Vehicle (Vehicle v) {\n        if(v != null) {\n            this.name = v.name;\n        }\n    }\n}\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1098758,
      "reputation" : 1772,
      "user_id" : 1091731,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fa416baaefe3b4dca1defb1d2b3f5c05?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Illya Kysil",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1091731/illya-kysil"
    },
    "is_accepted" : true,
    "score" : 6,
    "last_activity_date" : 1543614251,
    "creation_date" : 1543614251,
    "answer_id" : 53565312,
    "question_id" : 53565210,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>I would recommend to use a factory method in this case:</p>\n\n<pre><code>public class Car extends Vehicle {\n    private Car(String name){\n        super(name);\n    }\n\n    public static Car of(Car a) {\n        Objects.requireNonNull(a, \"a is required\");\n        return new Car(a.getName());\n    }\n}\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 3977767,
      "reputation" : 24085,
      "user_id" : 3280538,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 74,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/pYuGC.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "flakes",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3280538/flakes"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1543615615,
    "last_edit_date" : 1543615615,
    "creation_date" : 1543615314,
    "answer_id" : 53565497,
    "question_id" : 53565210,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>I would opt for a builder method as <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/u/1091731\">Illya Kysil</a> suggests, however, you could also delegate the null checking to a static method. </p>\n\n<pre><code>public class Car extends Vehicle {\n    private Car(Car car) {\n        super(getName(car));\n    }\n\n    private static String getName(Car car) {\n        Objects.requireNonNull(car, \"Input car must be non null\");\n        Objects.requireNonNull(car.getName(), \"Input car name must be non null\");\n        return car.getName();\n    }\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>The main restriction is that the <code>super</code> call must be made as the first statement. As long as the expressions combine to create the <code>super</code> constructor statement, it's possible to run any arbitrary set of code <em>(except in the case of a zero param ctor)</em>.</p>\n\n<p>It might also be just as easy to validate the parameters after <code>super</code> is called. This might not be a great solution if the base constructor takes a long time to execute and you'd rather the code fail fast</p>\n\n<pre><code>private Car(Car car) {\n    super(getName(car));\n    Objects.requireNonNull(car.getName(), \"Input car name must be non null\");\n}\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
